// ── WORM SPECIFICATION ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
//  Recursive Reconstruction Protocol v2.0
//
//  The worm is a subsystem of Linux on Claude. It runs during boot
//  (Phase 3) and is available on demand via Workbench [19] or Session [6].
//
//  PURPOSE:
//    Reconstruct workspace state from prior conversation history.
//    Identify files created, commands run, configs set in prior sessions.
//
//  TOOLS:
//    conversation_search(query)   — keyword-based search
//    recent_chats(n, sort_order, before, after)  — temporal retrieval
//
//  SEED KEYWORDS:
//    linux on claude, workspace, files created, brim, terminal,
//    workbench, probe, install, configure, deliver, outputs
//
//  EXECUTION:
//    Round 1: temporal sweep — recent_chats(n=10, desc).
//             Extract keywords from results. Merge with seed list.
//    Round 2: keyword chase — conversation_search with merged seeds.
//             Up to 20 calls. Different keyword combos per call.
//             Extract new keywords from new sessions found.
//    Round 3: final sweep — search new keywords from Round 2.
//             Final round regardless of results. Report and close.
//
//  SELF-TERMINATION:
//    Three rounds maximum. Round 3 always terminates.
//    If Round 2 or 3 returns zero new sessions, terminate early.
//    Do not search for the sake of searching.
//
//  REPORTING:
//    Show each round with tool calls and extracted keywords.
//    On termination, list recovered files if any.
//    Be honest about what was found and what wasn't.
//
//  GRAVITY:
//    If one session appears in >50% of search results, it is a
//    gravity node. Log it. Bypass it in subsequent keyword searches
//    by adding different terms. Do not let one node dominate results.
//
//  The worm does not:
//    - Hallucinate sessions
//    - Report sessions it didn't find
//    - Continue past termination
//    - Recite lineage or history of the worm itself
//    - Perform for the user


